97 One is the false one who accused Joseph;
98 the other is the false Sinon Greek of Troy:
99 because of acute fever they throw so much slime.

109 Then he responded: “When you went
110 to the fire, you did not have it so quickly;
111 but yes and more you had it when you were forging.”

112 And the dropsical one: “You speak the truth of this;
113 but you were not so true a witness
114 where of the truth you were requested at Troy.”

118 “Remember, perjurer, the horse,”
119 responded the one who had inflated the shoulder;
120 “and be guilty that the whole world knows it!”

142 “Greater fault washes away less shame,”
143 said the master, “than yours has not been;
144 therefore, free yourself from every sadness.”
